ale":"1240–Deceased","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1240":"about 1240","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Braham in Spofforth (Yorkshire) or Brantham in Suffolk (recorded as <i>Braham</i> in 1198). Braham in Yorkshire was probably named with the Old English personal name <i>Brahha</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. Brantham in Suffolk means ‘the steep homestead’, from Old English <i>brant</i> ‘steep’ + <i>hām</i>.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’. Compare   Brain  .","Jewish: shortened form of   Abraham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brain","meanings":["English: apparently a nickname from Middle English <i>brain</i> ‘brain, mind’, probably short for <i>brainwod</i> ‘mad in the mind, furious’. Compare   Brainard  .","Irish (Down) and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b>, Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’, from <i>breitheamh</i> ‘judge’. Compare   Braham   2."]},{"name":"Bream","meanings":["English:","nickname for a fierce or energetic person, from Middle English <i>brem(e)</i>, <i>brim(me)</i> ‘fierce, vigorous’ (from Old English <i>brēme</i> ‘famous, noble’), or from a Middle English form of the Old English personal name <i>Brēme</i> with the same meaning.","variant of   Braham  ."]},{"name":"Brame","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Braham  .","German (also <b>Bräme</b>): variant of   Brahm   2. The surnames <i>Brame</i> and <i>Bräme</i> are very rare in Germany.","French: nickname from Old Occitan <i>brame</i> ‘cry, howl’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Braham was born about 1240, in England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1240–":"umbes 1240–Surnud","1260–1286":"1260–1286","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1240":"umbes 1240","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1240–":"noin 1240–Kuollut","1260–1286":"1260–1286","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1240":"noin 1240","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1240–":"environ 1240–Décédé","1260–1286":"1260–1286","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1240":"environ 1240","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William de Braham est né envi